“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, which does not have access to the sea, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Marines are patrolling the Navy headquarters in La Paz.
Navy blue flags are hung on public buildings.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are covered with the slogan: “We have the right to the sea.
It’s our duty to get it back.”
In mainland Bolivia, the memory of the loss of the coast in a bloody conflict over natural resources with Chile in the 19th century is still alive – just like the longing for a new voyage across the Pacific Ocean.
This hope is perhaps the greatest after decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of the International Court of Justice, which it will receive on 1 October after five years of consultations.
“Bolivia has a momentum, a spirit of unity and impartiality and, of course, expects a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the international court’s decision on large screens across the country and hope that a court in The Hague will rule in favor of Bolivia, which argues that Chile must negotiate – after decades of volatile talks – Bolivia’s access to the sovereign sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, facing a controversial re-election battle next year, also has high expectations for Monday’s verdict.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court will not rule in favor of Bolivia — and even if it did, it would not have changed much.
The UN body based in the Netherlands does not have the authority to assign Chilean territory to Bolivia and will not decide on the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the international court’s decision comes just six months after hearing the final arguments means the case “wasn’t complicated,” said Paz Z<0xC3><0xA1>rate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And for the last four years, they haven't spoken out in favor of Bolivia, but they're probably going to cost it a lot.
“The current Bolivian government has taken advantage of the issue of access to the sea,” Zarate said.
Morales’s aggressive rhetoric has absorbed all the goodwill that may have remained from the Chileans, she explained.
The talks between Bolivia and Chile will continue at some point, but after that it will be extremely difficult to participate in the discussions.
The countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, the Bolivian representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court had taken a decision unusually quickly.
Monday will give Bolivia "an exceptional opportunity for a new era of relations with Chile" and the opportunity to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the maritime issue as a political backbone.
