North Korea: “Without confidence, we will not unilaterally disarm”
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations that the continued implementation of sanctions is causing growing mistrust in the United States and that under such conditions, North Korea will certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
At the annual meeting of the General Assembly of this world body, Ri Yong Ho said that North Korea has taken a number of "significant measures in good faith" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, tearing down the site for nuclear tests, and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a proper response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we will not be confident in national security, and under such conditions, we will in no way unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual measures, his statement was important because it did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri followed up on a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump from the first summit between the incumbent U.S. President and North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to seek “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” while promising security assurances to Trump’s North Korea.
North Korea wants an official end to the Korean War, which took place between 1950 and 1953, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also not given in to calls for the lifting of tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists that we must first disarm nuclear weapons and step up the pressure with sanctions to achieve our goals by force, and even oppose the declaration of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions could bring us to our knees is an unrealistic hope for people who don’t even know us.
The problem, however, is that the continued implementation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US president outlined at the United Nations Assembly earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the issue of nuclear disarmament had been discussed with South Korea and not the US, nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula would not have landed at such a dead end.”
Nevertheless, Ri’s tone of speech was quite different from the one last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly that an attack on the US mainland with North Korean missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim and his courage in taking disarmament measures at the United Nations, but said he still had a lot of work to do and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is nuclear-armed.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no timeline for this, saying: “It can take two years, three years or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia are of the opinion that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue resolutely without exception until we recognize the full, definitive and verified state of nuclear disarmament.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously adopted additional sanctions against North Korea to prevent the financing of North Korea’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Rome on the sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not end well.
When he left Pyongyang in July, he said progress had been made, and North Korea had already criticised him hours later, saying his demands were "gangster".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to demolish a missile test site and nuclear test infrastructure if the United States takes “appropriate action.”
Mr. Moon said the “appropriate measures” meant the security assurances Trump promised in Singapore and measures to normalize relations with Washington.
