Red tide news: Concentrations off the coast of Pinellas, Manatee and Saratoga are declining
A recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
In the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Saratosa, Charlotte and Collier, the FWC reported more diffuse flowering, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide extends about 130 miles from the coast north of Pinellas County to the southern counties of Lee.
The patches look about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, mean concentrations were reported in the County of Pinellas and along its coast, low to high concentrations in the County of Coller County, low to high concentrations in the County of Hillsborough, basic to high concentrations in the County of Manatee, basic to high concentrations in the County of Saratosa and along its coast, basic to medium concentrations in the County of Charette.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported from Northwest Florida in the past week.
